75. dispensare, manage, τῖε. use one's means with discretion. —fu- gienda, etc., i.e. consouna' right and wrong. But the words are used in the sense of the Stoic philosophy in reference to things which nature would suggest to us to seek and to avoid respectively3 cf. I. 3. 114.

76. tuo: in regard to his desires, which are in his own power to con· trol, so that the trouble arising from want of control is really his own fault. —rerum, circumstances, which it is not in his power to prevent, as it is in the other case.
